13. Roman to Integer solution in java
Here’s a clean and efficient Java solution for the Roman to Integer problem (LeetCode #13):

java
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

public class RomanToInteger {
    public int romanToInt(String s) {
        Map<Character, Integer> romanMap = new HashMap<>();
        romanMap.put('I', 1);
        romanMap.put('V', 5);
        romanMap.put('X', 10);
        romanMap.put('L', 50);
        romanMap.put('C', 100);
        romanMap.put('D', 500);
        romanMap.put('M', 1000);

        int result = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {
            int value = romanMap.get(s.charAt(i));
            
            // If the next value is larger, subtract current value
            if (i + 1 < s.length() && value < romanMap.get(s.charAt(i + 1))) {
                result -= value;
            } else {
                result += value;
            }
        }
        return result;
    }

    // Example usage
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        RomanToInteger converter = new RomanToInteger();
        System.out.println(converter.romanToInt("III"));    // Output: 3
        System.out.println(converter.romanToInt("LVIII"));  // Output: 58
        System.out.println(converter.romanToInt("MCMXCIV"));// Output: 1994
    }
}
🔑 Key Points:
Uses a HashMap to store Roman numeral values.

Iterates through the string:

If the current numeral is smaller than the next, subtract it.

Otherwise, add it.

Time complexity: O(n) (linear scan).

Space complexity: O(1) (fixed map size).

This is the most common and optimal approach for this problem.

