"flower".indexOf("flow")
In Java, the expression:

java
"flower".indexOf("flow")
returns 0.

Why?
The indexOf(String str) method checks where the substring str first appears in the given string.

"flower" starts with "flow", so the substring "flow" is found at index 0 (the beginning).

If the substring isn’t found, indexOf returns -1.

✅ Examples:

java
System.out.println("flower".indexOf("flow"));   // 0
System.out.println("flower".indexOf("owe"));    // 2
System.out.println("flower".indexOf("er"));     // 4
System.out.println("flower".indexOf("cat"));    // -1
This is exactly why the Longest Common Prefix solution works: it keeps shrinking the prefix until strs[i].indexOf(prefix) == 0, meaning the current string starts with that prefix.

