"flow".indexOf("flower")
In Java, the expression:

java
"flow".indexOf("flower")
returns -1.

Why?
The indexOf(String str) method looks for the first occurrence of the substring str inside the given string.

"flow" is shorter than "flower", and "flower" cannot be found inside "flow".

Since the substring doesn’t exist, indexOf returns -1.

✅ Examples to contrast:

java
System.out.println("flower".indexOf("flow"));   // 0  (because "flow" is at the start)
System.out.println("flow".indexOf("flower"));   // -1 (not found)
System.out.println("flow".indexOf("flo"));      // 0  (found at start)
System.out.println("flow".indexOf("ow"));       // 2  (found at index 2)
This highlights the directionality of substring checks: "A".indexOf("B") only succeeds if "B" is contained within "A".

